"issued_at": "1658673508030"
},
"oauthSuccess": true,
"cache": {4 items},
"identity": {
"username": "pgonzaleznetwork@brave-raccoon-mm7crl.com",
"name": "Pablo Gonzalez Alvarez",
"orgId": "00D3h000005XLUwEAO",
"userId": "0053h000002JF4cAAG",
"url": "https://brave-raccoon-mm7crl-dev-ed.my.salesforce.com",
"env": "Production"
}
}

These sessions typically are finite, they expire at a preconfigured time, resulting in the user being logged out the moment they try to interact with the app; I'm sure you've seen this behavior when you leave your Salesforce org open for a while.

But these fullstack apps also have the Salesforce access token/session Id stored in the server session. And this session also expires at some point (configured in the connected app, as we'll see later).

What happens if the salesforce access token expires, but the server session is still alive? Then the user would be able to interact with the app, but the app won't be able to contact Salesforce because the token is no longer valid.

So, how do you keep these 2 sessions in sync?


Setting a time-to-live for both sessions

In the case of HappySoup, I'm using express sessions with a Redis database. The session id is sent back to the browser as a cookie. Every request to the backend will have this cookie in the headers, and that's how we match the session.

In my session configuration, I have specified a TTL (time-to-live) value of 2 hours

const EXPIRE_TIME = 7200000;

let sessionStore = new RedisStore({
  host: redisConfig.host, 
  port: redisConfig.port, 
  client: redisClient,
  ttl:EXPIRE_TIME,
  disableTouch:true,
  prefix:'sfhs-sess:'
});

In the Salesforce connected app that controls HappySoup, I've also set the access token duration to 2 hours.

So this is a best effort to keep them both in sync. They should expire at the same time. However, I'm not convinced that's always the case, so I added some extra logic...


Using a Â express middleware to validate that both sessions are still alive

An express middleware is a function that runs on the backend every time a request is made to the backend (it's more than that but let's go with that definition).

So I created a middleware to validate that both sessions are alive. The basic logic is

 * Frontend makes request to backend
 * Before any kind of processing, the an express middleware checks if the redis session is still alive

   * If it is, then we need to check if the Salesforce session is alive

     * If it is, then make whatever request it's supposed to make




Here's how we check if the server session is alive

 let serverSessionAlive = (req.session.oauthSuccess || req.session.oauthInfo);

if(!serverSessionAlive){
    throw new ErrorHandler(404,'session-expired','server session has expired');
}

If it's not alive, we throw an error. If it's alive, we check if the Salesforce session is alive

let sfdcSessionAlive = await isSfdcSessionAlive(getConnection(req.session));
if(sfdcSessionAlive) next();	

If the session is alive, we call next to let the express server run the next function.


How to check if the Salesforce session is alive

I learned this bit by looking at the source code of Workbench. The isSfdcSessionAlive function does a tiny and quick API call to Salesforce, just to see if it's still alive. Think of it like a ping:

/**
 * Quick ping to salesforce to see if the oauth token is still alive
 */
async function isSfdcSessionAlive(connection){

    let isAlive = false;

    let api = soapAPI(connection);
    let response = await api.getServerTimestamp();

    if(response['soapenv:Envelope']['soapenv:Body'].getServerTimestampResponse){
        isAlive = true;
    }

    return isAlive;
}

The call we use is the getServerTimestamp which simply returns the timezone of the org.

So that's it! I think this works 99% of the cases :)

